WorkItem.Description:
Hi, in the code below the incomplete statement "var sumin = new" is compiling by concatenating the next line and automatically adding parentheses to the assumed type:

class RudeBoy {

	private greeting;
	
	public greet() {
		
		var sumin = new
		this.greeting = "Hello, *@#!!";
		
		//Compiles to
		//var sumin = new this.greeting() = "Hello, *@#!!";
		
	}
}

Comments.Message:
The problem is that it appears valid enough, because:

{{
function C() {}

var c = new
C()
}}

...is valid.

And so is:

{{
function C() {}

var c = new
C
}}

... Which TypeScript apparently attempts to "correct". 


Anyway... This should throw a ReferenceError. invalid LHS assignment

The idea of supporting JavaScript warts and all is not very appealing. Object instantiation should require that parentheses always follow the type.

Here is something else:  

var myvar = new();

// TS tries to be helpful and compiles this into

var vv = new ()();

// Runtime error  "Unexpected token )"

Back to untriaged -- we should treat this as a type error:

    var y;
    var x = new y = 4; // 'new y' is not a reference
